│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in                                 │
│ BinOpSameOpcodeHelper::InterchangeableInfo::getOperand(), specifically at the │
│ assertion FromCIValue.isZero() when converting a Shl instruction to an Add    │
│ instruction. This assertion is correct: converting shl x, C to add requires C │
│ == 0, otherwise the conversion is invalid. The reproducer contains a shl i32  │
│ 0, 1, which has a non-zero shift amount, so attempting to convert it to       │
│ add/sub/and/or/xor is invalid.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\nThe debug log    │
│ shows the SLP vectorizer analyzing a bundle including PHI nodes and then      │
│ \"Checking bundle:   %add = add i32 0, 0.\" Immediately after, it aborts in   │
│ InterchangeableInfo::getOperand(). The stack indicates convertTo() calls      │
│ getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp(I) to pick a SelectedOp, and then constructs a       │
│ Converter on I and calls Converter.getOperand(SelectedOp). The failure path   │
│ indicates that SelectedOp has opcode Add, while the current I being converted │
│ has opcode Shl (with CI=1), triggering the invalid conversion                 │
│ assertion.\n\n3. Root Cause                                                   │
│ Analysis:\nInstructionsState::getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp is responsible for     │
│ selecting whether the current instruction I should be matched to MainOp or    │
│ AltOp. It builds a BinOpSameOpcodeHelper Converter(MainOp), adds I and MainOp │
│ to it, and then decides to return AltOp if Converter.hasAltOp() and not       │
│ isAltShuffle, else returns AltOp or MainOp based on whether an alternate op   │
│ was seen. Critically, it does not verify that the chosen target opcode        │
│ (MainOp or AltOp) is actually a valid candidate opcode for the specific       │
│ instruction I being matched. As a result, the function may select AltOp with  │
│ opcode Add even when I is a Shl with non-zero constant, which is not          │
│ convertible to Add. Later, convertTo constructs a Converter on I alone and    │
│ attempts to compute operands for converting to the chosen opcode, hitting the │
│ assertion because the conversion is invalid for I.\n\nIn short,               │
│ getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp selects a target opcode based on global bundle       │
│ information (presence of AltOp) without checking convertibility of the        │
│ current I to that opcode.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit file            │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, function                     │
│ InstructionsState::getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp (lines 1228-1244) to ensure the   │
│ chosen opcode is a candidate for the specific instruction I. After building   │
│ the Converter with I and MainOp, determine the intended target opcode         │
│ (AltOp->getOpcode() if hasAltOp and isAltShuffle allows alternation,          │
│ otherwise MainOp->getOpcode()) and call                                       │
│ Converter.hasCandidateOpcode(TargetOpcode). If false, return nullptr to avoid │
│ invalid conversion. This prevents selecting an opcode that cannot be          │
│ converted from I.\n\nSuggested replacement body:\n\nInstruction               │
│ *getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp(Instruction *I) const {\n  assert(MainOp &&         │
│ \"MainOp cannot be nullptr.\");\n  if (I->getOpcode() ==                      │
│ MainOp->getOpcode())\n    return MainOp;\n  // Prefer AltOp instead of        │
│ interchangeable instruction of MainOp.\n  assert(AltOp && \"AltOp cannot be   │
│ nullptr.\");\n  if (I->getOpcode() == AltOp->getOpcode())\n    return         │
│ AltOp;\n  if (!I->isBinaryOp())\n    return nullptr;\n  BinOpSameOpcodeHelper │
│ Converter(MainOp);\n  if (!Converter.add(I) || !Converter.add(MainOp))\n      │
│ return nullptr;\n  // If we have an alternate op but this is not an           │
│ alt-shuffle case, we cannot use it.\n  if (Converter.hasAltOp() &&            │
│ !isAltShuffle())\n    return nullptr;\n  // Select target opcode and ensure I │
│ can be converted to it.\n  unsigned TargetOpcode = Converter.hasAltOp() ?     │
│ AltOp->getOpcode() : MainOp->getOpcode();\n  if                               │
│ (!Converter.hasCandidateOpcode(TargetOpcode))\n    return nullptr;\n  return  │
│ Converter.hasAltOp() ? AltOp : MainOp;\n}\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy validating    │
│ that the selected opcode (Main or Alt) is a candidate for conversion for the  │
│ current instruction I, we prevent getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp from returning an  │
│ opcode that cannot be converted, avoiding the invalid conversion path and     │
│ assertion in getOperand(). This fix is conservative: if I cannot be converted │
│ to the selected opcode, we return nullptr and the vectorization path will     │
│ treat the sequence as incompatible, avoiding the crash. It should resolve the │
│ provided reproducer without affecting valid cases."})                         │
