│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs in BinOpSameOpcodeHelper::InterchangeableInfo::getOperand(), │
│ specifically at the assertion FromCIValue.isZero() when converting a Shl      │
│ instruction to an Add instruction. This assertion is correct: converting shl  │
│ x, C to add requires C == 0, otherwise the conversion is invalid. The         │
│ reproducer contains a shl i32 0, 1, which has a non-zero shift amount, so     │
│ attempting to convert it to add/sub/and/or/xor is invalid.                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:                                                     │
│ The debug log shows the SLP vectorizer analyzing a bundle including PHI nodes │
│ and then "Checking bundle:   %add = add i32 0, 0." Immediately after, it      │
│ aborts in InterchangeableInfo::getOperand(). The stack indicates convertTo()  │
│ calls getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp(I) to pick a SelectedOp, and then constructs a │
│ Converter on I and calls Converter.getOperand(SelectedOp). The failure path   │
│ indicates that SelectedOp has opcode Add, while the current I being converted │
│ has opcode Shl (with CI=1), triggering the invalid conversion assertion.      │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ InstructionsState::getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp is responsible for selecting      │
│ whether the current instruction I should be matched to MainOp or AltOp. It    │
│ builds a BinOpSameOpcodeHelper Converter(MainOp), adds I and MainOp to it,    │
│ and then decides to return AltOp if Converter.hasAltOp() and not              │
│ isAltShuffle, else returns AltOp or MainOp based on whether an alternate op   │
│ was seen. Critically, it does not verify that the chosen target opcode        │
│ (MainOp or AltOp) is actually a valid candidate opcode for the specific       │
│ instruction I being matched. As a result, the function may select AltOp with  │
│ opcode Add even when I is a Shl with non-zero constant, which is not          │
│ convertible to Add. Later, convertTo constructs a Converter on I alone and    │
│ attempts to compute operands for converting to the chosen opcode, hitting the │
│ assertion because the conversion is invalid for I.                            │
│                                                                               │
│ In short, getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp selects a target opcode based on global    │
│ bundle information (presence of AltOp) without checking convertibility of the │
│ current I to that opcode.                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit file llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, function           │
│ InstructionsState::getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp (lines 1228-1244) to ensure the   │
│ chosen opcode is a candidate for the specific instruction I. After building   │
│ the Converter with I and MainOp, determine the intended target opcode         │
│ (AltOp->getOpcode() if hasAltOp and isAltShuffle allows alternation,          │
│ otherwise MainOp->getOpcode()) and call                                       │
│ Converter.hasCandidateOpcode(TargetOpcode). If false, return nullptr to avoid │
│ invalid conversion. This prevents selecting an opcode that cannot be          │
│ converted from I.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested replacement body:                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ Instruction *getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp(Instruction *I) const {                 │
│   assert(MainOp && "MainOp cannot be nullptr.");                              │
│   if (I->getOpcode() == MainOp->getOpcode())                                  │
│     return MainOp;                                                            │
│   // Prefer AltOp instead of interchangeable instruction of MainOp.           │
│   assert(AltOp && "AltOp cannot be nullptr.");                                │
│   if (I->getOpcode() == AltOp->getOpcode())                                   │
│     return AltOp;                                                             │
│   if (!I->isBinaryOp())                                                       │
│     return nullptr;                                                           │
│   BinOpSameOpcodeHelper Converter(MainOp);                                    │
│   if (!Converter.add(I) || !Converter.add(MainOp))                            │
│     return nullptr;                                                           │
│   // If we have an alternate op but this is not an alt-shuffle case, we       │
│ cannot use it.                                                                │
│   if (Converter.hasAltOp() && !isAltShuffle())                                │
│     return nullptr;                                                           │
│   // Select target opcode and ensure I can be converted to it.                │
│   unsigned TargetOpcode = Converter.hasAltOp() ? AltOp->getOpcode() :         │
│ MainOp->getOpcode();                                                          │
│   if (!Converter.hasCandidateOpcode(TargetOpcode))                            │
│     return nullptr;                                                           │
│   return Converter.hasAltOp() ? AltOp : MainOp;                               │
│ }                                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By validating that the selected opcode (Main or Alt) is a candidate for       │
│ conversion for the current instruction I, we prevent getMatchingMainOpOrAltOp │
│ from returning an opcode that cannot be converted, avoiding the invalid       │
│ conversion path and assertion in getOperand(). This fix is conservative: if I │
│ cannot be converted to the selected opcode, we return nullptr and the         │
│ vectorization path will treat the sequence as incompatible, avoiding the      │
│ crash. It should resolve the provided reproducer without affecting valid      │
│ cases.                                                                        │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
